I used to get so frustrated with myself every time I would encounter a setback on my fitness journey, like catching a cold or traveling for more than a few days. I would stress over it and beat myself up. However, over time I realized that setbacks are an unavoidable part of any journey and having them is absolutely fine. More so, they should be accepted and embraced.

And I did just that this past week. I had a cold, I took care of it and I was kind to myself about it. I knew my gym is not going to blacklist me and my bike is still going to love me back when I'm ready for it 💝

Let's celebrate setbacks as they are an opportunity to rest, reset, and to reevaluate what needs reevaluation ✌️

It appears as though my abs did not betray me while I was ill 🫣

The Miami Marathon came and went, it was an event not to be missed. I had low expectations for myself as I rarely run, and my prep for the event started two weeks before and consisted of 6 runs. However, I run at a pretty good pace, and surprised myself.

My concern is that I might've caught the running bug, and will have to add running to my already busy workout schedule 😅

Regardless, now that I am aware of my potential, I'm signing up for the next year with a high goal in mind 💃

Since I started working with my coach @ulissesabbud, my training intensity has increased and so did my nutritional demands. 

Prepping juice in batches, saves me time and allows me to meed those demands, since fresh juice is rich in micronutrients and antioxidants my body needs.

I love juicing all of the green veggies and herbs, and ginger is an absolute must, as it reduces inflammation. Then I add some fruits for taste. I used oranges and an apple this time but looking forward to using pineapple for my next batch.

If you’re feeling fancy, go ahead and peel the oranges. I didn’t feel fancy. However, I scrubbed the peel thoroughly to remove pesticides.

Ingredients: 
Kale
Spinach
Parsley
Cilantro (don’t hate me for this one, I love cilantro 😭)
Celery
Carrot
Orange
Apple
Ginger
Lime

Juicer @omegajuicing

For a cyclist, aggression from drivers is a common occurrence but that was just pure hate.

I want to use this incident as an opportunity to remind ourselves of the importance of being able to see past our differences, and treat, even those who we dislike or disagree with, with respect and compassion 🫶

My daily protein power smoothie recipe. It helps me with my high nutritional demands, and it also is delicious. I always look forward to it 😋

• Banana (I buy a bunch, chop them up and freeze for smoothies)
• Oat milk
• Protein powder (using my fav @vitalproteins)
• Pumpkin seeds - 2 tbsps
• Hemp seeds - 1 tbsp
• Flaxseed meal - 1 tbsp
• Peanut butter (from dark roast peanuts 🤌) - 1 tbsp
• Spinach - as much as I can fit in the blender
• Ice

Last week was my birthday, it’s my 43rd. I never celebrate it in a big way, and this year I chose to spend it by the pool in good company. I put my phone away, for the most parts, and was present in the moment, which was wonderful. Not a lot of pictures were taken but it gave me more time to enjoy the moment. 

As you get older, time starts flying by progressively faster. That teaches you to cherish it, and prioritize what really matters. It forces you to reevaluate what’s worth your energy, and what isn’t. It makes you realize that you don’t have to prove anything to anyone but yourself, and not everyone has to like you or agree with you. It really is okay to be different and have a difference of opinion. 

The older you get, the easier it becomes to just breathe, and not give a crap about the distractions that do not add to your life experience in a positive way.

I’m looking forward to the next level of enlightenment ✌️ 

I love you, guys, and I’m grateful for you. I have been fortunate enough to have an online community that is positive and supportive. Thank you so much! ❤️

Yesterday I felt the need to take a full day off, mentally and physically. I spent the day lounging in bed with my brain disconnected from any attempt to contemplate, ponder or plan, but most importantly from being hard on myself. Which is an unfortunate trait many of us struggle with.

We live in a fast-paced world, and sadly it has become the norm to overextend ourselves, and to exist in a chronic state of fatigue. Often going through the motions, forgetting to stop and smell the roses. 

Well, yesterday my body forced me to stop and be present, and thank goodness! What a difference a day of mental rest can do, I feel enthusiastic and brand new 💁‍♀️

Take that break, be kind to yourself, you will pick up where you left off 🫶

Have the best weekend! 🥰

This week I started practicing intermittent fasting. I’m following the 16:8 diet regiment, in which you fast for 16 hours and eat during the 8-hour window. 

I have always stayed away from fasting as I would easily get lightheaded if I skipped a meal, but after practicing fasting for several days, I came to realize that it’s surprisingly doable, and I even get competitive with myself and try to pushhhh it, lol. The reason I turned to fasting, is an inflammation in my body that I’ve been experiencing lately, it’s been causing minor ailments one after another, and for someone like me who’s rarely sick, that’s very concerning.

There are numerous benefits of Intermittent fasting, it has been shown to reduce oxidative stress and inflammation, factors that contribute to aging and many diseases. Also, when you fast, your HGH level increases, which improves strength and metabolism, and your insulin level drop significantly, which promotes fat burning. Furthermore, your cells start an important cellular waste removal process called autophagy. In this process, the cells break down and metabolize broken and dysfunctional proteins that build up inside them over time. Essentially, autophagy slows down aging by decreasing age-associated deterioration.
However, the studies I’ve looked at suggest that autophagy begins between 24 to 48 hours of fasting. Going forward, I’ll most certainly experiment with longer fasts.

Who’s on the intermittent fasting wagon as well?? 🐷

Despite my having to master self-reliance early on in life, the holiday season always remains a poignant reminder of the absence of a loving family. As everyone gathers with their loved ones, the sense of solitude can feel profound and is an emotionally challenging journey. 

Whether you have a loving family or not, unfortunately, many of us still feel isolated during the holidays. By acknowledging these feelings of sadness, loneliness, or even a sense of alienation during this time, and actively taking steps to navigate through them with compassion, you're taking control of your emotional well-being and preventing resentment or prolonged negativity from taking root. 

Amidst these challenging emotions, it's crucial to remind yourself that even in moments of solitude, you are never truly alone, there are countless others navigating similar feelings. 

On the bright side, overcoming challenges is what makes us grow.

Merry Christmas and Happy Holidays!
